今天要寫 PopupMenu 的時候，發現在要用點選複選框的項目會重置狀態，一般我都會這樣定義一個 PopupMenu 的。
當按鈕 btn 點擊後便執行：
btn.setOnClickListener(v -&gt; &#123;
    PopupMenu popupMenu &#x3D; new PopupMenu(this, btn);
    popupMenu.getLayoutInflater().inflate(R.menu.main_menu, popupMenu.getMenu());
    popupMenu.setOnMenuItemClickListener(i -&gt; &#123;
        i.setChecked(!i.isChecked());
        return true;
    &#125;);
    popupMenu.show();
&#125;);


但這樣做，如果你不是要做被選框，只是純粹一個項目的話，這樣問題不大，不然會有一個問題，就是複選框勾選後會自動重置到未勾選狀態。
原來是因為這個 PopupMenu 是靠按鈕 btn 生成的，所以每當這個 PopupMenu 彈出後，都會重新建立，導致到看似會有勾選後重置的結果。

解決問題要解決這個問題，我們不應該把 PopupMenu 以按鈕 Button 的點擊事件來生成，而是在活動 Activity 生成。
PopupMenu popupMenu;

popupMenu &#x3D; new PopupMenu(this, btn);
popupMenu.inflate(R.menu.main_menu);
popupMenu.setOnMenuItemClickListener(i -&gt; &#123;
    i.setChecked(!i.isChecked());
    return true;
&#125;);

再用按鈕 btn 的點擊事件呼喚 PopupMenu：
btn.setOnClickListener(v -&gt; popupMenu.show());

完整代碼public class MainActivity extends AppCompatActivity &#123;

    ActivityMainBinding binding;
    PopupMenu popupMenu;

    @Override
    protected void onCreate(Bundle savedInstanceState) &#123;
        super.onCreate(savedInstanceState);
        binding &#x3D; ActivityMainBinding.inflate(getLayoutInflater());
        setContentView(binding.getRoot());

        popupMenu &#x3D; new PopupMenu(this, binding.button);
        popupMenu.inflate(R.menu.menu);
        popupMenu.setOnMenuItemClickListener(i -&gt; &#123;
            i.setChecked(!i.isChecked());
            return true;
        &#125;);

        binding.button.setOnClickListener(v -&gt; popupMenu.show());
    &#125;
&#125;


那就不會重置了，問題解決。

Wanna type and compile code in your app on your own device? In this article, we will learn how to create an online Java compiler application using CodeX API, a powerful API which provides functions to compile and execute program codes.
Here is the documentaion of CodeX API .







特别注意
CodeX API is still in early stages development and not recommended to be used in production since it’s deployed in a Free tier on render, which slows down the API sometimes. Plus, this is a simple online compiler application using CodeX API only. Therefore, there won’t be advanced features of compilation.










However, a good news is that CodeX API supports standard inputs e.g. Scanner in Java, which helps us write simple programs with inputs on mobile.

Manifest Configuration
Set permissionSince we are gonna build online compiler application, it requires Internet and network access. Therefore, we have to add these codes in AndroidManifest.xml to grant permissions for the application.
&lt;uses-permission android:name&#x3D;&quot;android.permission.INTERNET&quot; &#x2F;&gt;
&lt;uses-permission android:name&#x3D;&quot;android.permission.ACCESS_NETWORK_STATE&quot; &#x2F;&gt;


Allow HTTP URLs accessStarting from Android 9 (API level 28) and above, it disallows HTTP URLs by default. It will throw error messages informing that cleartext HTTP traffic is not permitted if there are programs accessing HTTP URLs.
If the URL can’t be really changed and connected from HTTP to HTTPS, while you want to use the HTTP URL to continue building your project.
Here are two popular solutions of resolving HTTP traffic errors:

Solution 1 - Cleartext TrafficIn AndroidManifest.xml, set android:usesCleartextTraffic property to true.
&lt;application
    android:usesCleartextTraffic&#x3D;&quot;true&quot;&gt;
&lt;&#x2F;application&gt;


Solution 2 - Allow connections to specific siteI used this method before, and I still recommend using it. The second way is to allow connections to specific sites.
Unlike Solution 1, we need to create a new XML file named network_security_config.xml  in /res/xml/.
&lt;network-security-config&gt;
&lt;domain-config cleartextTrafficPermitted&#x3D;&quot;true&quot;&gt;
    &lt;domain includeSubdomains&#x3D;&quot;true&quot;&gt;...&lt;&#x2F;domain&gt;
&lt;&#x2F;domain-config&gt;
&lt;&#x2F;network-security-config&gt;


The ... to be replaced is your desired HTTP URL. Once you put it inside the &lt;domain&gt;, it can be permitted and be accessed.






小提示
For example, if I want to enable this HTTP URL: bluewhaleyt.ddns.net, then I will do the following like this.
&lt;network-security-config&gt;
&lt;domain-config cleartextTrafficPermitted&#x3D;&quot;true&quot;&gt;
    &lt;domain includeSubdomains&#x3D;&quot;true&quot;&gt;bluewhaleyt.ddns.net&lt;&#x2F;domain&gt;
&lt;&#x2F;domain-config&gt;
&lt;&#x2F;network-security-config&gt;


After doing this, you need to set android:networkSecurityConfig in the AndroidManifest.xml.
&lt;application
    android:networkSecurityConfig&#x3D;&quot;@xml&#x2F;network_security_config&quot;&gt;
&lt;&#x2F;application&gt;

Done, it’s now ready to be accessed.






小提示
Both solutions are great. To make it simple, I prefer Solution 1, which is much easier.


Create LayoutIn this project, we will use Sora Editor as a code editor instead of using EditText. With this, we can type codes with syntax highlighting. However, the guide of using Sora Editor will not be written here. You can read this related article for more info.
Here are dependencies of Sora Editor and the layout in case you are familiar with them.
implementation(platform(&quot;io.github.Rosemoe.sora-editor:bom:0.20.2&quot;))
implementation(&quot;io.github.Rosemoe.sora-editor:editor&quot;)
implementation(&quot;io.github.Rosemoe.sora-editor:language-textmate&quot;)

&lt;?xml version&#x3D;&quot;1.0&quot; encoding&#x3D;&quot;utf-8&quot;?&gt;
&lt;LinearLayout
    xmlns:android&#x3D;&quot;http:&#x2F;&#x2F;schemas.android.com&#x2F;apk&#x2F;res&#x2F;android&quot;
    xmlns:app&#x3D;&quot;http:&#x2F;&#x2F;schemas.android.com&#x2F;apk&#x2F;res-auto&quot;
    xmlns:tools&#x3D;&quot;http:&#x2F;&#x2F;schemas.android.com&#x2F;tools&quot;
    android:layout_width&#x3D;&quot;match_parent&quot;
    android:layout_height&#x3D;&quot;match_parent&quot;
    android:orientation&#x3D;&quot;vertical&quot;&gt;

    &lt;io.github.rosemoe.sora.widget.CodeEditor
        android:id&#x3D;&quot;@+id&#x2F;editor&quot;
        android:layout_width&#x3D;&quot;match_parent&quot;
        android:layout_height&#x3D;&quot;match_parent&quot; &#x2F;&gt;

&lt;&#x2F;LinearLayout&gt;


RequestNetwork Java FilesSketchware Pro provides the utils of network request components, RequestNetwork.java and RequestNetworkController.java. These are the useful utility program files helping us fetch data from URL easily.
We can simply bring these files to our project in case you don’t have them.









Of course, you can use others like HttpURLConnection to do the same job.



       RequestNetwork.java
       1.36 KB







       RequestNetworkController.java
       6.99 KB











注意
These files were simplified with lambda expressions.

Besides, we need to add okhttp dependency.
implementation(platform(&quot;com.squareup.okhttp3:okhttp-bom:4.10.0&quot;))
implementation(&quot;com.squareup.okhttp3:okhttp&quot;)

Why RequestNetwork files?We will use POST endpoint to execute the program script and fetch the compilation output later.
requestNetwork.startRequestNetwork(RequestNetworkController.POST, url, &quot;api&quot;, requestListener);

These files help us do network data api fetching stuffs, which is efficient for us.

Use CodeX APIAs aforementioned, we will build an online compiler application with CodeX API.
This is the URL that the API is located in: 
https:&#x2F;&#x2F;api.codex.jaagrav.in

This URL is supposed not to be and unable to be directed but we will use this API to compile and execute program codes.

Create a Compiler classIn order to make our project be clean, we will create a new Java class Compiler.java to do it so.
Your Compiler.java should be like this:
public class Compiler &#123;
    ...
&#125;

In this class, there will be two methods, init() and compile(), both of them must be public since they will be called in MainActivity.java later.
Define VariablesNow, initialize the following variables.
private static String url &#x3D; &quot;https:&#x2F;&#x2F;api.codex.jaagrav.in&quot;;

private static HashMap&lt;String, Object&gt; map &#x3D; new HashMap&lt;&gt;();
private static HashMap&lt;String, Object&gt; data &#x3D; new HashMap&lt;&gt;();

private static RequestNetwork requestNetwork;
private static RequestNetwork.RequestListener requestListener;

private static ModernDialog.Builder dialog;
private static AlertDialog progressDialog;

ModernDialog.Builder belongs to ModernDialog library which is created by myself. If you want to use this library, you can read this article.






小提示
Instead of using ModernDialog, you can either use AlertDialog or MaterialAlertDialogBuilder.


Initialize RequestNetworkTo start a new instance of RequestNetwork, add the code below.
RequestNetwork requestNetwork &#x3D; new RequestNetwork(this);

We will create a new method init() to do the initialization stuffs.
public static void init(Activity activity) &#123;
    requestNetwork &#x3D; new RequestNetwork(activity);
&#125;


Use RequestListenerThis is the basic start of RequestListener.
RequestListener requestListener &#x3D; new RequestNetwork.RequestListener() &#123;
    @Override
    public void onResponse(String tag, String response, HashMap&lt;String, Object&gt; responseHeaders) &#123;

    &#125;

    @Override
    public void onErrorResponse(String tag, String message) &#123;

    &#125;
&#125;;








小提示
onResponse() is to fetch data from URLs if there’s no errors occuring.onErrorResponse() is to throw errors during the issues of fetching data from URLs.


Loading dialogIn both onResponse() and onErrorResponse() methods, we need to define a progress dialog to tell users that the data from URLs is fetching, since it would take time to fetch.
public static void compile(Activity activity) &#123;
    ...
&#125;

Create a new method compile() and add the progress dialog.







注意
In this article, progress dialog will not be detailed, see article.

&lt;?xml version&#x3D;&quot;1.0&quot; encoding&#x3D;&quot;utf-8&quot;?&gt;
&lt;LinearLayout xmlns:android&#x3D;&quot;http:&#x2F;&#x2F;schemas.android.com&#x2F;apk&#x2F;res&#x2F;android&quot;
    android:layout_width&#x3D;&quot;match_parent&quot;
    android:layout_height&#x3D;&quot;match_parent&quot;&gt;
    &lt;LinearLayout
        android:layout_width&#x3D;&quot;match_parent&quot;
        android:layout_height&#x3D;&quot;wrap_content&quot;
        android:orientation&#x3D;&quot;horizontal&quot;
        android:padding&#x3D;&quot;20dp&quot;&gt;
        &lt;ProgressBar
            android:id&#x3D;&quot;@+id&#x2F;pbLoading&quot;
            style&#x3D;&quot;?android:attr&#x2F;progressBarStyle&quot;
            android:layout_width&#x3D;&quot;wrap_content&quot;
            android:layout_height&#x3D;&quot;wrap_content&quot;
            android:layout_marginLeft&#x3D;&quot;10dp&quot;
            android:layout_marginRight&#x3D;&quot;20dp&quot; &#x2F;&gt;
        &lt;TextView
            android:id&#x3D;&quot;@+id&#x2F;tvText&quot;
            android:layout_width&#x3D;&quot;wrap_content&quot;
            android:layout_height&#x3D;&quot;wrap_content&quot;
            android:layout_gravity&#x3D;&quot;center&quot;
            android:text&#x3D;&quot;TextView&quot; &#x2F;&gt;
    &lt;&#x2F;LinearLayout&gt;
&lt;&#x2F;LinearLayout&gt;

public static void compile(Activity activity) &#123;
    View view &#x3D; activity.getLayoutInflater().inflate(R.layout.dialog_progress, null);
    TextView tv &#x3D; view.findViewById(R.id.tvText);
    tv.setText(&quot;Compiling, please wait ...&quot;);

    progressDialog &#x3D; new MaterialAlertDialogBuilder(activity).create();
    progressDialog.setView(view);
    progressDialog.setCancelable(false);
    progressDialog.show();
&#125;

When there are responses, dismiss the progress dialog.
@Override
public void onResponse(String tag, String response, HashMap&lt;String, Object&gt; responseHeaders) &#123;
    progressDialog.dismiss();
&#125;

@Override
public void onErrorResponse(String tag, String message) &#123;
    progressDialog.dismiss();
&#125;

Connection Error AlertOnce again, this is an online compiler which requires Internet connection. We need to alert users activating it before starting to code.
To do this, we need to use onErrorResponse() method.
@Override
public void onErrorResponse(String tag, String message) &#123;
    progressDialog.dismiss();

    dialog.setTitle(&quot;No Internet&quot;);
    dialog.setMessage(message);
&#125;


Fetch dataWe will use Gson to stringify JSON, add dependency:
implementation &#39;com.google.code.gson:gson:2.10&#39;

To put response as a part of JSON to data using Gson:
data &#x3D; new Gson().fromJson(response, new TypeToken&lt;HashMap&lt;String, Object&gt;&gt;()&#123;&#125;.getType());

Therefore, we have the following code.
@Override
public void onResponse(String tag, String response, HashMap&lt;String, Object&gt; responseHeaders) &#123;
    progressDialog.dismiss();

    data &#x3D; new Gson().fromJson(response, new TypeToken&lt;HashMap&lt;String, Object&gt;&gt;()&#123;&#125;.getType());
&#125;


OutputIn the docs of CodeX API, we can see there is a sample output of a NodeJS Program.
&#123;
  &quot;timeStamp&quot;: 1672439982964,
  &quot;status&quot;: 200,
  &quot;output&quot;: &quot;Enter your value: 12\n&quot;,
  &quot;error&quot;: &quot;&quot;,
  &quot;language&quot;: &quot;py&quot;,
  &quot;info&quot;: &quot;Python 3.6.9\n&quot;
&#125;

This code is exactly to get the output:
data &#x3D; new Gson().fromJson(response, new TypeToken&lt;HashMap&lt;String, Object&gt;&gt;()&#123;&#125;.getType());

You can simply inspect its content via Log.
Log.d(TAG, String.valueOf(data));







小提示
TAG is your Java class. Usually, if we define TAG, we will use the code like this below:
private final String TAG &#x3D; MainActivity.class.getName();

the TAG‘s value will be defined as MainActivity.


This is an example output from Android Studio’s Logcat:
&#123;
    &quot;timeStamp&quot;: 1.672711656435E12,
    &quot;output&quot;: &quot;Hello World!\nScanner input: 43&quot;,
    &quot;language&quot;: &quot;java&quot;,
    &quot;error&quot;: &quot;&quot;,
    &quot;status&quot;: 200.0,
    &quot;info&quot;: &quot;openjdk 11.0.17 2022-10-18 OpenJDK Runtime Environment (build 11.0.17+8-post-Ubuntu-1ubuntu218.04) OpenJDK 64-Bit Server VM (build 11.0.17+8-post-Ubuntu-1ubuntu218.04, mixed mode, sharing)&quot;
&#125;


CompilationCodeX API compilation needs requirement below:

code     - the code to be compiled
language - the programming language to be used
input    - the execution of program input







小提示
Here’s the programming languages available for CodeX API:

js - NodeJS (JavaScript)
java - Java
c - C
cpp - C++
cs - C#
py - Python
go - GoLang

The inline code is the language as a payload. For instance, if you want to compile C++, the compilation shouldn’t be loaded as c++. Instead, it should be cpp.


Here’s how to set the configuration.
map.put(&quot;code&quot;, strCode);
map.put(&quot;language&quot;, strLang);
map.put(&quot;input&quot;, strInput);

requestNetwork.setParams(map, RequestNetworkController.REQUEST_BODY);

We are going to extend the compile() method with three more parameters: text, lang, and input.
public static void compile(Activity activity, String text, String lang, String input) &#123;

    map &#x3D; new HashMap&lt;&gt;();
    map.put(&quot;code&quot;, text);
    map.put(&quot;language&quot;, lang);
    map.put(&quot;input&quot;, input);

    requestNetwork.setParams(map, RequestNetworkController.REQUEST_BODY);
&#125;

After the setting is done, starts the RequestNetwork.
requestNetwork.startRequestNetwork(RequestNetworkController.POST, url, &quot;api&quot;, requestListener);








小提示
url is &quot;https://api.codex.jaagrav.in&quot;, which has already been defined. If you do not, add this code.
private static String url &#x3D; &quot;https:&#x2F;&#x2F;api.codex.jaagrav.in&quot;;


During the compilation, there will be one of two results, Compilation Success and Compilation Failed.

Compilation SuccessWe will declare it as a success situation if there’s no error response. Then, display the compilation output.
if (data.get(&quot;error&quot;).toString().equals(&quot;&quot;)) &#123;
    dialog.setTitle(&quot;Compilation output&quot;);
    dialog.setMessage(data.get(&quot;output&quot;).toString());
&#125;








小提示
data.get(&quot;error&quot;) is to fetch error responses if there’s any.data.get(&quot;output&quot;) is to fetch the output of compilation if there’s no error responses.
In order to check and display as a String, we need to set toString() for them.


Compilation FailedThe compilation failed means there’s error response during the compilation. If there are errors, display them.
else &#123;
    dialog.setTitle(&quot;Compilation error&quot;);
    dialog.setMessage(data.get(&quot;error&quot;).toString());
&#125;









注意
Don’t forget to show the dialog after the if statement.
dialog.show();


Following instructions above, your code should be like below:
@Override
public void onResponse(String tag, String response, HashMap&lt;String, Object&gt; responseHeaders) &#123;
    progressDialog.dismiss();
    data &#x3D; new Gson().fromJson(response, new TypeToken&lt;HashMap&lt;String, Object&gt;&gt;()&#123;&#125;.getType());

    if (data.get(&quot;error&quot;).toString().equals(&quot;&quot;)) &#123;
        dialog.setTitle(&quot;Compilation output&quot;);
        dialog.setMessage(data.get(&quot;output&quot;).toString());
    &#125;
    else &#123;
        dialog.setTitle(&quot;Compilation error&quot;);
        dialog.setMessage(data.get(&quot;error&quot;).toString());
    &#125;

    dialog.show();
&#125;


Call Compiler classWe’re almost there, we’re now in the step of calling methods from Compiler class.
Your MainActivity.java should be like this.
public class MainActivity extends AppCompatActivity &#123;
    private ActivityMainBinding binding;

    @Override
    protected void onCreate(Bundle savedInstanceState) &#123;
        super.onCreate(savedInstanceState);
        binding &#x3D; ActivityMainBinding.inflate(getLayoutInflater());
        setContentView(binding.getRoot());
    &#125;
&#125;








注意
View Binding - binding is not required to be used in this project. However, it is a good way to get rid of using findViewById().
For instance:
&#x2F;&#x2F; get TextView&#39;s text using findViewById()
String tv &#x3D; findViewById(R.id.tv);
String text &#x3D; tv.getText().toString();

&#x2F;&#x2F; get TextView&#39;s text using view binding
String text &#x3D; binding.tv.getText().toString();

Therefore, using view binding has several advantages:

Supports null safety. There won’t be Attempt to invoke virtual method on a null object reference errors since the components are binded in view binding. It also prevents non-existent views or components being called.
Reduces boileplate code, since findViewById() requires to be defined again if it is being used again, which takes too many places of the entire program and wastes on the operations. If it comes to view binding, it literally eliminates these problems.
Facilitates type safety, since the binding class that’s generated matches the views declared in the layout file.



To compile, call compile() from the Compiler class.
Compiler.compile(this, strCode, strLang, strInput);


Handle input executionNow, we need to implement the compilation of input. We will make a new dialog with its custom view in MainActivity.java. Again, ModernDialog is used, you can use others.
&lt;?xml version&#x3D;&quot;1.0&quot; encoding&#x3D;&quot;utf-8&quot;?&gt;
&lt;LinearLayout xmlns:android&#x3D;&quot;http:&#x2F;&#x2F;schemas.android.com&#x2F;apk&#x2F;res&#x2F;android&quot;
    android:layout_width&#x3D;&quot;match_parent&quot;
    android:layout_height&#x3D;&quot;match_parent&quot;
    android:orientation&#x3D;&quot;vertical&quot;
    android:paddingLeft&#x3D;&quot;10dp&quot;
    android:paddingRight&#x3D;&quot;10dp&quot;&gt;
    &lt;com.google.android.material.textfield.TextInputLayout
        android:layout_width&#x3D;&quot;match_parent&quot;
        android:layout_height&#x3D;&quot;wrap_content&quot;&gt;
        &lt;EditText
            android:id&#x3D;&quot;@+id&#x2F;et&quot;
            android:layout_width&#x3D;&quot;match_parent&quot;
            android:layout_height&#x3D;&quot;wrap_content&quot;
            android:hint&#x3D;&quot;Input&quot; &#x2F;&gt;
    &lt;&#x2F;com.google.android.material.textfield.TextInputLayout&gt;
&lt;&#x2F;LinearLayout&gt;

@Override
protected void onCreate(Bundle savedInstanceState) &#123;
    ...
    dialog &#x3D; new ModernDialog.Builder(this)
            .setDialogStyle(ModernDialog.DIALOG_STYLE_BOTTOM_SHEET)
            .setView(R.layout.dialog_edittext)
            .setTitle(&quot;Leave it empty if no inputs is needed.&quot;)
            .setPositiveButton(null, v -&gt; &#123;
                EditText et &#x3D; dialog.dialogBS.findViewById(R.id.et);
                String input &#x3D; et.getText().toString();
                Compiler.compile(this, binding.editor.getText().toString(), &quot;java&quot;, input);
            &#125;)
            .show();
&#125;


Lastly, call init() from the Compiler class to initialize the RequestNetwork.
Compiler.init(this);








特别注意
The initialization - init() should be executed before the compilation compile(). Otherwise, the program will never work and show onResponse() or onErrorResponse() with Attempt to invoke interface method on a null object reference.

To make sure you don’t get lost, here’s the code:
public class MainActivity extends AppCompatActivity &#123;
    private ActivityMainBinding binding;

    @Override
    protected void onCreate(Bundle savedInstanceState) &#123;
        super.onCreate(savedInstanceState);
        binding &#x3D; ActivityMainBinding.inflate(getLayoutInflater());
        setContentView(binding.getRoot());

        Compiler.init(this);
    &#125;
&#125;

You may ask, where does compile() code? It should be executed on a button click or else.
Here’s an example of defining a Button and executing its click event.
&lt;Button
    android:id&#x3D;&quot;@+id&#x2F;btn&quot;
    android:layout_width&#x3D;&quot;wrap_content&quot;
    android:layout_height&#x3D;&quot;wrap_content&quot;
    android:text&#x3D;&quot;Compile&quot; &#x2F;&gt;

binding.btn.setOnClickListener(v -&gt; &#123;
    dialog &#x3D; new ModernDialog.Builder(this)
            .setDialogStyle(ModernDialog.DIALOG_STYLE_BOTTOM_SHEET)
            .setView(R.layout.dialog_edittext)
            .setTitle(&quot;Leave it empty if no inputs is needed.&quot;)
            .setPositiveButton(null, v -&gt; &#123;
                EditText et &#x3D; dialog.dialogBS.findViewById(R.id.et);
                String input &#x3D; et.getText().toString();
                Compiler.compile(this, binding.editor.getText().toString(), &quot;java&quot;, input);
            &#125;)
            .show();
&#125;)


