Hello, welcome to this blog. Today, we’re going to use Sora Editor with TextMate in version 0.18.1 using Java.







特别注意
The source codes that show in this article may be deprecated or not working as the development of Sora Editor is mushrooming rapidly. Thanksfully, the codes still work till 0.21.0.
However, if there’s any breaking changes of the programs and methods, there will be an updated version in the foreseeable future.



Why this post?Due to the open source code of Sora Editor’s demo application is all about in Kotlin, which is not friendly for the developers who may not figure out how to write and understand Kotlin codes, me also XD. In view of this, I’m here to show you how to use Sora Editor with TextMate in version 0.18.1 using Java.

Resources
Theme filesIf you don’t want to find and download yourself, you can download the theme files here. In this article, I will provide a theme of light mode and dark mode for one i.e. quietlight and darcula respectively.



       quietlight.json
       12.07 KB







       darcula.json
       14.75 KB





Language filesTo make Textmate work, you need to prepare the files yourself. That said, you need to find relative resources from tm4e. Here, I will provide Java language files as an example.
In the java.zip, there are several files you need, actually, they are the syntax files for Java, namely java.tmLanguage.json and language-configuration.json files.



       java.zip
       7.88 KB




Besides this, you need a grammar base i.e. languages.json to load all the languages.



       languages.json
       231.00 B





Embedded languagesEmbedded language is to extend the syntax from one to more. That said, you can have CSS &lt;style&gt; and JavaScript &lt;script&gt; or other syntaxes with html language.



       html.zip
       15.94 KB







       css.zip
       17.35 KB







       javascript.zip
       21.05 KB




